The paper presents an algorithm for computing the Lyndon array of a string as a byproduct of the inversion of the Burrows-Wheeler transform. This involves data structures and algorithms related to string processing, which suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) sub-category. Additionally, the paper involves the use of a stack and the comparison of different linear-time algorithms, which are common topics in the cs.CC (Computational Complexity) sub-category. The paper also proposes a new balanced parenthesis representation for the Lyndon array that uses bits of space and supports constant time access, which suggests that it may belong to the cs.IT (Information Theory) or cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) sub-categories. Finally, the paper compares its algorithm with known approaches, which suggests that it may also belong to the cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-category, as this sub-category often involves the comparison and evaluation of different algorithms.
